'''Kenny Baker''' ([[August 24]], [[1930s|1934]] &ndash; [[August 13]], [[2016]]<ref name="NY Times" />) was a [[Wikipedia:United Kingdom|British]] actor best known as the man inside of [[R2-D2]] in the ''Star Wars'' film series. Baker had also worked with George Lucas outside of the ''Star Wars'' films, with an uncredited role as a Nelwyn band member in [[Willow (film)|''Willow'']], as well as a role as the Goblin Corps in [[Wikipedia:Labyrinth (1986 film)|''Labyrinth'']].

Baker's other films include [[1980]]'s ''The Elephant Man'', [[1981]]'s ''Time Bandits'', and the [[1986]] Jim Henson film ''Labyrinth''. In the late [[1990]]s, Baker launched a stand-up comedy career. Kenny is a first-class mouth-organ player and rates his guest appearance with the James Coutts Scottish Dance Band at Hugh McCaig's Silverstone Party in July 1997 as probably his "finest musical experience."

==Biography==
[[File:KennyPaploo.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Baker's lesser known role as Paploo the Ewok]]
Kenny Baker, at 3 feet, 8 inches (112 cm) tall, was a circus and cabaret performer with entertainer [[Jack Purvis]] when [[George Lucas]] hired him to be the man inside R2-D2 in ''Star Wars'' in [[1977]]. Baker appears in the first six theatrical ''Star Wars'' films, although stock footage was used for much of R2-D2's role in [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Revenge of the Sith'']].<ref name="interview">{{WebCite|url=http://metro.co.uk/2009/10/27/kenny-baker-240855|text=Kenny Baker|work=Metro.co.uk|archivedate=20170804221248}}</ref> Baker played an additional role in [[1983]]'s [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']] as [[Paploo]], the [[Ewok]] who stole an [[Galactic Empire|Imperial]] [[74-Z speeder bike|speeder bike]].<ref name="SW.com">{{SW|url=news/kenny-baker-the-actor-who-brought-r2-d2-to-life-passes-away|text=Kenny Baker, the Actor Who Brought R2-D2 to Life, Passes Away}}</ref>

In [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''Star Wars'': Episode VII ''The Force Awakens'']], Baker was credited as "R2 Consultant." R2-D2 in the movie was represented by actor [[Jimmy Vee]].<ref name="Making SW">{{WebCite|url=http://makingstarwars.net/2015/09/little-actor-jimmy-vee-is-artoo-detoo-in-star-wars-episode-viii|text=Little Actor Jimmy Vee Is Artoo-Detoo In Star Wars: Episode VIII?|author=Ward, Jason|date=2015-09-16|archivedate=20200806134332}}</ref>

Baker was hospitalized on [[April 9]], [[2008]] because of a "mystery illness,"<ref name="Contact Music">{{WebCite|url=http://www.contactmusic.net/star-wars/news/r2-d2-actor-struck-down-with-mystery-illness_1065169|text=R2-D2 Actor Struck Down With Mystery Illness|author=WENN|date=2008-04-10|archivedate=20170320224814}}</ref> and on August 13, 2016, passed away at the age of 81, 11 days before his 82<sup>nd</sup> birthday.<ref name="NY Times" />

